# Performance Rules

These apply to hot paths: per-frame code (`BuffSystem.Tick`, `CooldownManager.Tick`, `StateMachine<TOwner>.Tick`, `IState<TOwner>.Tick`, any `MonoBehaviour.Update`/`FixedUpdate`/`LateUpdate`) and per-invocation code that runs frequently in combat (`DamagePipeline.Execute`). Initialization and configuration-loading code (constructors, `Awake`, ScriptableObject loading) is not held to these constraints — allocating there is fine.

## Allocations

Avoid allocations inside hot-path methods. This includes:
- `new List<T>()`, `new Dictionary<K,V>()`, or any collection allocation inside `Tick`/`Update` — allocate once in the constructor or `Awake`, reuse and clear instead.
- Boxing value types into `object` or an interface inside a hot path (e.g. passing an `int`/`float`/custom struct somewhere it gets implicitly converted to `object` or a non-implementing interface type). Note: storing an interface reference (`ICombatEntity`) inside a `struct` like `DamageContext` does **not** box, since `ICombatEntity` is implemented by reference types (`Player`/`Enemy`) in this project — `DamageContext` is a `readonly struct` specifically to avoid a heap allocation for the context object itself on every damage calculation, not to avoid boxing (see `type-design.mdc`).
- Per-frame string concatenation or `string.Format`/interpolation for anything that isn't user-facing debug output behind a flag.
- `Delegate.GetInvocationList()` inside `EventBus.Publish` — merges handlers on Subscribe/Unsubscribe instead.

## LINQ

Avoid LINQ inside `Tick`/`Update` methods — `Where`, `Select`, `OrderBy` and similar allocate iterators and closures per call. LINQ is acceptable in initialization and configuration code (e.g. building a list of `IDamageModifier` from a config at startup) where it runs once, not every frame.

```csharp
// Wrong — inside BuffSystem.Tick, runs every frame
var expired = _instances.Where(i => i.RemainingTime <= 0).ToList();

// Correct — manual loop, no per-frame allocation
for (int i = _instances.Count - 1; i >= 0; i--)
{
    if (_instances[i].RemainingTime <= 0)
    {
        _instances.RemoveAt(i);
    }
}
```

## Component Access

`GetComponent<T>()` must be called at most once per object, during initialization, and its result cached in a field. Never call `GetComponent<T>()` inside `Update` or any per-frame method. See `architecture.mdc` for the full dependency-injection rule this is part of.

## Collection Reuse

Where a collection's contents change every frame but its capacity is roughly stable (e.g. a list of active buffs, a list of nearby enemies), reuse the same collection instance and `Clear()` it rather than allocating a new one each frame.

## State Instance Reuse

`IState<TOwner>` implementations may be allocated once per entity during initialization (`Player`/`Enemy.Initialize`) and reused across transitions. `ChangeState(cachedInstance)` is correct. Do not `new` state objects inside `IState.Tick` or other per-frame hot paths — that conflicts with the allocation rules above. Stateless flyweight state objects are preferred.

## Cooldown HUD — Pull, Not Push

Continuous cooldown radial fill is **pulled** by `PlayerHUD` via
`AbilitySystem.CooldownQuery.GetNormalized(abilityIndex)` — do not publish per-frame cooldown
progress events. `CooldownManager` publishes **`CooldownStartedEvent`** and **`CooldownEndedEvent`**
only (discrete transitions). This matches industry UI practice and keeps the event bus off
hot paths.

## AbilityContext Passing

`AbilityContext` is not a per-frame hot path, but use **`in AbilityContext ctx`** on all `IAbility` / `AbilityBase` methods to avoid defensive copies of the multi-field struct.
